# GitHub Sync Rule (Commit + Push Workflow)

Goal: keep the GitHub `origin` branch updated whenever the project changes.

## Safety checks (must)
- Never include secrets or generated artifacts in commits.
  - Do not commit `.env.local`, `.DS_Store`, `node_modules/`, or any other local-only files.
- If `.gitignore` is missing/insufficient, ask the user to confirm before staging anything.

## When to propose a sync
- After finishing any meaningful change (code/features/docs) and before starting unrelated work, check repo state with:
  - `git status`
  - If there are changes worth syncing, propose the next step to the user.

## What to ask the user
- Ask for confirmation before creating a commit or pushing to GitHub.
  - Example prompt to user: "Sync to GitHub now? (This will run `git add -A`, create a commit, and push.)"

## Sync commands (what the user/agent runs after confirmation)
- `git add -A`
- `git commit -m "<short message describing the change>"`
- `git push -u origin main`

## First-time setup reminder
- Ensure a GitHub remote exists:
  - `git remote -v`
- Ensure the branch is `main`:
  - `git branch -M main`

